#for loop that checks if the calue in the gegraphy column is one of the values determined by me, it then assigns a value or moves on.
for i in cado.index:
    if cado.loc[i, 'geography'] in ['California', 'South Carolina', 'West Tex/New Mexico', 'Northern New England']:
        cado.loc[i, 'region_type'] = 'state'
    elif cado.loc[i, 'geography'] in ['Midsouth', 'Northeast', 'Southeast', 'West']:
        cado.loc[i, 'region_type'] = 'major'
    elif cado.loc[i, 'geography'] in ['Total U.S.']:
        cado.loc[i, 'region_type'] = 'us'
    else: 
        cado.loc[i, 'region_type'] = 'metro'

# Renaming columns for avocado sizes, also renaming the year column ahead of following problems
cado = cado.rename(columns={'4046': 'small_hass', 
                            '4225': 'large_hass', 
                            '4770': 'xlarge_hass',
                           'year': '_year'})

avocado_clean = avocado_date

avocado_metro_top5 = avocado_metro_sum.nlargest(5,'total_volume')

Question 7:

#Split data to conventional and organic
avocado_cali_conv = avocado_cali[(avocado_cali['type'] == 'conventional')]
avocado_cali_org = avocado_cali[(avocado_cali['type'] == 'organic')]

#Change price column names in preparation of joining data
avocado_cali_conv = avocado_cali_conv.rename(columns={'average_price': 'average_price_conv'})
avocado_cali_org = avocado_cali_org.rename(columns={'average_price': 'average_price_org'})

#Take the mean of each month of each year of each city
avocado_cali_conv_avg = avocado_cali_conv.groupby(['geography','year', 'month'])['average_price_conv'].mean().reset_index()
avocado_cali_org_avg = avocado_cali_org.groupby(['geography','year', 'month'])['average_price_org'].mean().reset_index()

#join organic and conventional to one data frame by city, year, and month
avocado_cali_merge = avocado_cali_conv_avg.merge(avocado_cali_org_avg, on = ['geography', 'year', 'month'])

#take the difference of the organic and conventional avocados for each index
avocado_cali_merge['price_delta'] = avocado_cali_merge['average_price_org'] - avocado_cali_merge['average_price_conv']

#merge the year and month column to allow for plotting
avocado_cali_merge['y_m'] = avocado_cali_merge['year'].astype(str) + '-' + avocado_cali_merge['month'].astype(str)

#convert the merged string into a datetime format for the plotter to understand.
avocado_cali_merge['y_m'] = pd.to_datetime(avocado_cali_merge['y_m'], format='%Y-%m')

Plotting

warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

plot1 = (ggplot(avocado_cali_merge,aes(x = 'y_m', y = 'price_delta', color = 'geography')) + 
    theme_bw() +

    labs(x = 'Date', y = 'P1: Price Difference (organic - conventional)') +
    ggtitle('Average Price Difference') +

        figure_size = (12,5),

plot2 = (ggplot(avocado_cali_merge,aes(x = 'y_m', y = 'price_delta', color = 'geography')) + 
    theme_bw() +
    facet_wrap('geography') +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth() +
    labs(x = 'Date', y = 'P2: Price Difference (organic - conventional)') +

    theme(
        figure_size = (12,5),

plot3 = (ggplot(avocado_cali_merge,aes(x = 'geography', y = 'price_delta', fill = 'geography')) + 
    theme_bw() +

    ggtitle('Price Difference Boxplot') +

        figure_size = (12,5),

        )
)

Plot Analysis:

The plots will give us a quick understanding, however, it does not offer the complete picture.

P1: We can see the trends that the different cities have had in their avocado price differences, mainly that San Francisco had large differences, however, it has evened out in the past few years. Although, this plot gives us insight in the relative trends of the different cities, it might not provide a complete picture, so another plot was created.

P2: this plot supports the conclusion that P1 was not enough to tell the complete picture. We can see that San Francisco and Sacramento have very similar patterns with a price difference hike late 2016 to early 2017, whereas Los angeles has, what looks like the most stable pattern.

P3: in P3 we can see a summary of the total values when time is removed, this shows us that San Francisco still have the highest values, however, it reveals that there is in fact some difference between Sacramento and San Francisco as this time San Diego matches the mean values of San Francisco, however, San Francisco stil has more outliers.

#Is it just me or does this variable sound like a delicious sandwich.
#https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.melt.html
avocado_cali_melt = avocado_cali.melt(value_vars = ['small_hass', 'large_hass', 'xlarge_hass'],
                                      var_name = 'size_type',
                                      value_name = 'volume',
                                      id_vars = ['geography', 'type'])

#Take the sum of volumns for each city and add make it into a column that matches the sum to the right city
#https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.transform.html
total_volume = total_volume = avocado_cali_melt.groupby(['geography', 'type'])['volume'].transform('sum')

#calculate the percentage
avocado_cali_melt['percentage'] = avocado_cali_melt['volume'] / total_volume
#plot
(ggplot(avocado_cali_melt, aes(x='geography', y = 'percentage', fill = 'size_type')) +
     theme_bw() +
     facet_wrap('type') +
     geom_bar(stat = 'identity') +
     scale_y_continuous(breaks = [0,0.25,0.5,0.75,1], labels = ['0', '25%', '50%', '75%', '100%']) +
     labs(x = 'Region of California', fill = 'Avocado Size', y = False) +
     theme(figure_size = (12,5))
)

house = pd.read_csv(r"C:\Users\tuke-\Desktop\1_GSB544_Computing_and_Machine_Learning\Week_2\LAB2\data\housing-prices.csv")

house[['month', 'year', 'temp']] = house['Mon-Yr'].str.split('/', expand = True)

#delete extra columns
house = house.drop(['Mon-Yr', 'temp'], axis = 1)

house = house[['year', 'month', 'Los Angeles', 'Sacramento', 'San Francisco', 'San Diego']]

#Melt to match the other dataset
house = house.melt(value_vars = ['Los Angeles', 'Sacramento', 'San Francisco', 'San Diego'],
                                      var_name = 'geography',
                                      value_name = 'home_price',
                                      id_vars = ['year', 'month'])

#Convert values to the correct format
house['year'] = house['year'].astype('int64')
house['month'] = house['month'].astype('int64')
house['home_price'] = house['home_price'].astype('int64')

#Rename values in year column
house['year'] = house['year'].replace({15: 2015, 16: 2016,17: 2017,18: 2018,19: 2019,20: 2020})
